  "prompt": "I'm a US citizen and my boyfriend is Argentinean; if we get married in the US, how long will it take for him to be qualified to work in the US?",
  "response": "If you are a U.S. citizen and you marry your Argentinean boyfriend, he can apply for a marriage-based green card, which allows him to live and work in the United States. Here\u2019s a general breakdown of the process and timeline:\n\n1. **Marriage**: You must first get legally married.\n\n2. **Petition**: As a U.S. citizen, you will need to file Form I-130, Petition for Alien Relative, to establish your relationship.\n\n3. **Adjustment of Status**: If your boyfriend is in the U.S. on a valid visa, he can apply for Adjustment of Status using Form I-485, Application to Register Permanent Residence or Adjust Status. If he is outside the U.S., he will go through consular processing.\n\n4. **Work Authorization**: While the Adjustment of Status application is pending, he can apply for a work permit using Form I-765, Application for Employment Authorization. It typically takes about 4 to 6 months for this to be processed, though times can vary.\n\n5. **Green Card Approval**: Once the I-130 and I-485 (if adjusting status) are approved, he will receive a green card, which gives him permanent resident status and the right to work in the U.S. Full processing from starting the I-130 to receiving the green card may take around 8 to 14 months or longer, depending on various factors, including service center processing times and whether any issues arise.\n\nAlways check the USCIS website or consult with an immigration attorney for the most accurate and up-to-date information regarding your specific situation and the process based on current immigration laws and procedures.",
